results.name: Array read by rows, where the n-th row (of A120256(n) terms) lists the positive divisors, not occurring earlier in the array, of the n-th Fibonacci number.
comment: A permutation of the natural numbers, ordered by A001177 and ties broken by the number itself. Inverse permutation is A119745. - _Martin Fuller_, Sep 10 2006
link: Michael De Vlieger, Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..12333 (rows 2 <= n <= 100)
example: Fibonacci(9) = 34; and the divisors of 34 are 1, 2, 17 and 34. Of these divisors, 1 and 2 occur earlier in the array.
So the 9th row of the array is [17, 34].
mathematica: f[t_] := Append[t, Select[Divisors[Fibonacci[Length[t] + 1]], FreeQ[Flatten[t], # ] &]]; Flatten@Nest[f, {}, 20] (* _Ray Chandler_, Jun 14 2006 *)
